ğŸ”¹ 1. Master Node (Control Plane)
API Server â€“ Entry point for kubectl & tools

Scheduler â€“ Places pods on appropriate worker nodes

Controller Manager â€“ Handles Replication, Node Monitoring, etc.

etcd â€“ Distributed key-value store (stores all cluster state)

ğŸ”¸ 2. Worker Nodes
kubelet â€“ Communicates with API Server, manages pods on the node

kube-proxy â€“ Maintains network rules on nodes for service traffic

Container Runtime â€“ e.g., containerd or Docker (runs containers)

ğŸ§© 3. Core Components
Pods â€“ Smallest deployable unit in k8s

Containers â€“ Inside pods, runs the application

ReplicaSet â€“ Ensures a specified number of pod replicas are running

Deployment â€“ Declarative updates to Pods and ReplicaSets

ğŸ”§ 4. Configuration & Secrets
ConfigMap â€“ Inject config data (e.g., env vars, config files) into pods

Secret â€“ Stores sensitive data (passwords, tokens, etc.)

âœ… Mounted as files or environment variables into pods.

ğŸ“ 5. Storage
Volumes â€“ Persist data across container restarts

PersistentVolume (PV) â€“ Actual storage

PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) â€“ Request for PV by user

ğŸ”— 6. Networking
Service â€“ Exposes a set of Pods as a network service

ClusterIP â€“ Internal access

NodePort â€“ External access via node IP and static port

LoadBalancer â€“ External load balancing

Ingress â€“ HTTP routing to services, managed by Ingress Controller

ğŸŒ 7. Add-ons
CoreDNS â€“ Internal DNS

Dashboard â€“ Web UI (optional)

Metrics Server / Prometheus â€“ Monitoring

